{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cbcea321-d94b-4a26-84a6-44b8c5737861","content":"\n\nIn your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Scenario | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| App backgrounded | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| App resumed | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Destroying` |\n\n> `Backgrounding` is iOS/Mac Catalyst only — use it to save state before the OS may terminate your app.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"47380b3c-98c2-4808-8ff6-e84a25a6870a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":392},"id":"9b5aaf46-b9a0-408c-a99a-4e30b98b1664","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:40:46.316Z","parentId":"5bd9af4d-0e43-4c1a-8d99-39e96ab8d9ab"}
